GAME_EXPECT is to be used when the game engine is built in debug mode to make sure we exit informatively, where we would otherwise crash; it is not meant for defensive programming, and should never guard against crashes. The macros live in misc/assert_log.h and are gated by GAME_ASSERT_ENABLE in game_primitives.h, which stays commented out for normal builds. When the toggle is off, GAME_EXPECT and GAME_EXPECT_RET compile to nothing so hot paths pay zero cost. When it is on, a failed condition logs through AssertLog::log with a short message that should name the call site and the broken invariant. Prefer that over silent early returns that hide the same bug in release and debug alike.

Write expects against facts the caller already promised: a non-null GameState after begin, a live unit after the unit scan filtered empty slots, a seat index inside m_player_n. Soft outcomes such as “this unit is not a worker” or “turn limit reached” stay ordinary control flow and must not be wrapped in GAME_EXPECT. GAME_EXPECT_RET exists for non-void helpers that should log and return a failure value while asserts are enabled; with asserts disabled it also compiles out, so release builds still assume the invariant holds. Do not use expects to paper over nullable optional state that legitimate callers may hit every turn.

The practical rule is: if violating the condition would crash or corrupt match state, expect it. Messages should stay short and stable so stderr greps stay useful across refactors. AssertLog::log prints the message to stderr, flushes, and exits the process with status 1, so a failed expect never continues into undefined follow-on work. GAME_EXPECT_RET still writes a return for readability, but that path is unreachable once log has run with asserts enabled. Debug builds therefore fail fast and loudly; release builds omit the checks and require the same invariants to hold without the safety net.
